author: @pacifiedfools
processed_text: In order to prevent price inflation in a monopoly in a capitalist system, you would have to have an organization independent of the company set the price of the product. In a capistalist system the goal of the company is to make as much profit as possible so prices would rise if the company sets its own prices.

author: @pacifiedfools
processed_text: Under the current system, competition does create the incentive to keep quality high and drive prices down, and monopolies do result in quality loss and price inflation. The reason that monopolies result in price inflation is because consumers have no other companies to buy from which allows the one company to charge high prices, quality loss occurs for the same reason. The company can become complacent regarding quality output since it cannot be in jeopardy in a monopoly. contd.

author: @pacifiedfools
processed_text: Suppose you have five small companies that are about the same size and make a product and one company that is five times larger and makes the same product. The five smaller companies have to order parts in smaller quantities than the larger companies; buying in smaller quantities generally costs more money. The larger company buys in larger quantities, which allows it to sell the product for less and still make a profit. contd.

processed_text: Kurzweil is right about the exponential nature of technological progress, because he can identify the cause of it: the hierarchical nature of human knowledge (which Newton was speaking of when he spoke of "standing on the shoulders of giants"). In my Objectivist perspective, free-market capitalism can best solve those two problems.

author: @justgivemethetruth
processed_text:
I don't really know if knowledge is growing exponentially ... if it is it has a denominator that is almost infinite.  Even at our old knowledge growth rate humans have a wisdom deficit, so that wisdom deficit is just getting worse.

Plus, the people on the top are finding all kinds of ways to limit information to the rest of us making our knowledge irrelevant.

What is growing is the amount of data we have on human behavior and people ... and that is the scariest thing.

Brains are incredibly complex.  If you're curious to know more, there is a wealth of knowledge on scholar.google that goes into these neuroscience topics in much more detail. Thanks for your comment deadvulcano.

author: @deadvulcano
processed_text:
A sperm whales brain is ~6 times the size of a human brain.  Whales do have more neocortex surface area compared to humans.  However, whales do not have as many levels of cortical hierarchy.  Whales actually have fewer total neurons and available connections--only 2/3 that of humans at best.

Humans may be in a sweet spot for brain size without giving up too much space to supporting brain structure (glial).  This is essentially why bigger isn't always better for brains--unless you are a zombie.

author: @panpiper
processed_text: Paddy makes a classic error with the gold standard, stating that there is not enough gold. This is completely incorrect. It does not matter if a dollar is backed by an ounce of gold, a gram, a milligram or a microgram. The quantity is irrelevant, what matters is only that it is backed. The whole point is to deny the government (the Fed) the ability to simply invent money out of nothing, as it is precisely that, that is the cause of our economic booms, busts and current doldrums.

author: @panpiper
processed_text: Paddy makes reference to "disastrous deflation", failing to discern between the two possible causes of deflation, an error all Keynesians make. A monetary deflation where the money supply actually goes down is indeed a potential disaster. But a price deflation caused by increases in productivity is all upside. Keynesians treat the two as if they were the same thing, inflating the money supply in order to stop it, with horrible consequence to the economy and people's lives.

author: @panpiper
processed_text: Certainly their misfeasance was greatly encouraged by the moral hazard of that implicit guarantee of government bailout. I wish to god there was no such impetus on the part of government.

author: @panpiper
processed_text: Note too that the current strategy for getting the economy out of it's doldrums is for the Federal Reserve to offer massive amounts of new money to banks at below inflation rate interest, while government does everything it can to boost the housing market.

author: @panpiper
processed_text: I do not disagree with you that government subsidizing failure is a huge problem, but it was not that which caused the market to fail. They did that 'after' the market failed. What caused the market to fail was the central bank (the Federal Reserve) offering new money to banks (including investment banks) at below inflation rate interest (effectively paying them to take new money) while the government simultaneously did everything it could to engender a massive housing bubble.

author: @nathankw
processed_text: I think you misunderstand. He's not saying that the "light is particles" bit is not the case. He's saying it's not the case that light is slowed down by gravity like a ball is slowed down if you throw it upwards. Light is affected by gravity but that's because of the way mass bends space time as explained by general relativity. Light always travels at the same speed (in a vacuum) so can't be slowed.

author: @kurtilein3
processed_text:
aaah, first big mistake spotted around 4:50 : Light IS PARTICLES. Its Photons, its quantized, its particles allright. "We now know this isnt the case" Bullshit, it is the case.

If light would NOT be particles, then x-rays and gamma rays wouldnt be dangerous, solar panels wouldnt work, lasers wouldnt work, and you couldnt get a sunburn.

Can't speak on his behalf... but from reading his work, I believe he would not advocate a direct democracy.
As you may already know, the US is a republic because the idea of the 'many' imposing their will over the 'few' was abhorrent to the founding fathers. It is the very opposite of liberty/freedom! Pretty sure they had considered that, but knew better.
What happens when the outcome of a very personal issue to you and your family is 51/49 and YOU are the 49%? Careful what you wish for.

author: @JayBazuzi
processed_text:
In some ways, we all live better than any king in history. In access to calories, ease of transportation & communication, indoor climate control, etc. This is the bounty of technology.

And yet, in some ways we all live worse than peasants and primitives: community, pollution, play, connection to nature. Why is that?

Charles had merely an hour to cover topics that deserve much deeper analysis. If his statements here seem half-baked, but you're curious, you might check out his books.

author: @momerath42
processed_text: My solution in 461 characters or less: Everyone owns at least one device to manage their identity.  People publish statements about their (usually conditional) intentions and facts they wish known; pull in others' statements through their webs of trust. Ontologies, shared through the same mechanism, allow determination of the likely consequences of the combined intentions.  (Non)automatic negotiation mechanisms bring disparate predictions closer.  Code is updated through the WoT like any 'fact'.

author: @Flaser01
processed_text:
Mistakes:
a) Thorium first captures a neutron THEN undergoes a beta-decay chain.
b) Weapons grade uranium is *90%* enriched, not 20%... it's NOT easy!
c) For a thorium-fuel cycle reactor, the proliferation issues are more similar to how Plutonium is bred, then the enrichment issues of a "simple" U-235 bomb. The high gamma emitter U-232 contamination supposedly protects the pure U-233 bred in such a reactor , but (unfortunately) this is not as clearcut as it's sometimes made out to be.

author: @robshred66
processed_text: Anyway, in a nutshell, the reason for our financial woes are unsustainably artificially low fed funds rates (what's gonna happen when interest rates inevitably rise and the bond market fails, esp when you've got the Fed purchasing almost all our T-bonds, lol--why do you think that is?--we can't just keep printing are way down, because then it'll be inflation that tanks us), debt spending, artificial markets propped up and backed by the government, etc. Deregulation didn't even really happen.

author: @robshred66
processed_text: And if you look closer at the boom/busts before the Fed in 1914, it's the same thing--government induced. Let's take the 1873 one for example. The government was heavily subsidizing railroads, and there still was a central banking system, just not so powerful as the Fed. The only reason why we're not Greece right now (we've racked up more debt than all of the Eurozone combined) is because we have a printing press. But is this a good thing? All logic points to NO. (cont.)

author: @robshred66
processed_text: Fannie and Freddie wrote most of the bad loans, the ARMs, etc--because the government doesn't care. They just want to promote home buying, regardless of how artificial and unsustainable it might be. And those folks on wall street were just along for the ride. The thing that most affected it, though, was the cheap money from the Federal Reserve. It's monetary policy that is usually behind every boom. When you extend banks an unlimited supply of cheap credit, what do you think will happen? (cont.)

author: @robshred66
processed_text: What's wrong is that the government, via regulations and policies, created a market that never would've been there in the free market--the sub prime market. Banks used to operate under a 3-6-3 rule: deposit 3, loan at 6, 3:00 tea/tee time. The GSA separate financial and commercial banking, and yet with the FDIC it still ensures deposits. This is bad, because the banks are covered now--hence their risky behavior, which never would have happened without it. Fannie and Freddie..(cont.)

author: @robshred66
processed_text: First of all, there's the SEC, there was countless bills in place, and already countless regulations on the books. But if you're arguing that this was the cause, this was an act of government (look who our secretaries of treasury were, and are for that matter (Geithner was president of Fed branch of NY). The thing is, deregulation does nothing be restrict healthy growth. (Cont.)

author: @david203
processed_text: @usability Yes, that is very true. Transcending (TM or NSR) is not necessary for anyone advanced enough to be able to stop thinking and experience inner joyful silence. In my experience as a teacher, very few people are able to exercise this degree of natural control over the process of thinking. Note that we don't just follow thoughts when we transcend--that is useless because it keeps us in the field of thinking. This is just a distraction when we want to discover what lies beyond thinking.

author: @usability101
processed_text: Hi David, I believe what Eckhart is saying is that we are trying NOT to think. In my experience, following a thought in meditation is the opposite of presence for me. Your experience may be different and that's so ok— there are many different paths to truth.

author: @david203
processed_text: Eckhart reached Self-realization spontaneously. The rest of us can use some help to get past the distracting thoughts and become aware of the underlying pure or unbounded consciousness. I recommend the natural mental technique of transcending, taught by various organizations such as Transcendental Meditation (TM) or Natural Stress Relief (NSR). Transcending starts the easy way, by thinking a thought. But then it allows you to follow that thought back to its origin in pure awareness. Try it.

author: @ElvisTheAnnointed
processed_text:
But in order to understand the way your true self expresses itself, through your actions, etc, you also have to understand your environment: how it acts on you and you act on it.  And the only way to fully understand your environment is to understand everything that shaped your environment, i.e., everything that exists.
In other words, if you find your "self" in your actions, the only way to have a full sense of self is to understand the entire universe.

author: @ElvisTheAnnointed
processed_text: The ego-death isn't the loss of the sense of self, it's just realizing that your sense of self is external to you.  In other words, you find your identity in your thoughts and actions, which aren't you, but expressions of you, in the same way that a painting expresses something about the artist.  To fully know your true self, you have to let go of everything that is external to yourself, or else fully understand your expressions of yourself to know what they reveal about you.

processed_text: @randomguy634 Actually, Graeber is all for having a Jubilee. He certainly doesn't consider debt to be a valid moral concept. To paraphrase him, "morals are like debt, except they're not like debt at all, and it's ridiculous to even try to make a comparison."

author: @randomguy634
processed_text: @VoidOnTuesday I think the point of that story was to highlight the fact that a moral concept of debt can override even things that anyone would consider morally absolute. He's not saying 'Debt killed these babies, therefore debt is evil', rather he's questioning what debt means as a moral concept.

author: @arkinestesia
processed_text: For us the party means returning to a remote and undifferentiated state, the being of time: a return that is also a beginning... Well, despite that digression, we would greatly appreciate it if you could consider our request and agree a booking for your services to make a unique presentation here in Medellín. Let us know your decision and your available dates, so we can agree the details and make the necessary travel arrangements. Thank you very much. We really hope you'll feel able to say yes.

author: @arkinestesia
processed_text:
For us in Colombia a great party has the mythical value of the ancients: we dance, we become the music, almost animalistic, like angels of lights and shadows. 
We believe a party can be a cosmic operation where laws and things get lost in a mass primordial form; in a happy chaos of sonorous colors, in a meeting of contrary elements and principles to provoking the rebirth of life.

author: @arkinestesia
processed_text: Dear SNOOP DOOG BOSS We are writing from Medellin, Colombia. Your music is greatly appreciated and respected here and it would be great if you could find the time to come and let us see and hear for ourselves. We are more than just businessmen: we try to go beyond the purely commercial and pursue our interests in substantial music and the artistic and ritual value of great representation.

author: @SculptedThoughts
processed_text: Your rational faculty in your dreams does not work properly, so you can't be held responsible for a lot of it. I heard from an old psychology teacher once (haven't cross referenced yet) that your MORAL faculty does work, however, and that you would never do anything in your dreams that you would not ethically do in real life. I think this is interesting, because I've killed people without justification in dreams, and, for a while after I started philosophizing, began waiting for justification.

All we know is that, in Limbo, death is a kick. What that kick does isn't even alluded to in the film. author: @xtraa
processed_text:
Hm, for me the spinning to is actually the spin in the movie itself. We can argue with Kant, who said that everything we see is not the thing itself, but what we expect it to be. (Like a flask that also could be used as a hammer, but we see it as a flask). 

As Mr. Johnson said, the spinning top is totally useless as a totem. His reality is actually a layer of the dream of his wife. He invented a totem, the ring, within this dream. His wife realized it so her suicide was the right decision.

author: @Mutex50
processed_text: @weathychef I don't know how you can see the irrational behavior of those graphs and not see that it is not intuitive.  IRV reduces the spoiler effect a bit, but it still doesn't eliminate it.  In the early rounds it is easier for the less viable candidates to knock off the more viable candidates that stand a chance against the candidate you don't like.  Also, voting against your own candidate can help him win in some situations.

author: @Mutex50
processed_text: @TerrorBlack The general would only have 2 candidates. The open primary with approval voting would be used to get those candidates.

author: @Mutex50
processed_text: @vexgodglove A different voting system can allow us to vote for candidates that will not be corrupted.  Also, it will greatly speed up our ability to get a constitutional amendment passed to get CFR.

author: @Mutex50
processed_text: @wealthychef You can look at the website I linked to to see why it is unintuitive.  Also SJVoter shows some of the problems of IRV on his channel.  He is a douche bag  propagandist, but he does make SOME good points.

author: @Mutex50
processed_text:
@wealthychef IRV is better than plurality, but it has a lot of problems.
1) It is a pain in the ass to implement and tally results. Approval voting can use the same technology we currently use.
2) The results are unintuitive.  For a good comparison of the voting systems go to zesty(dot)ca(slash)voting(slash)sim
3) A lot of people don't understand IRV when it is explained to them.  The concept seems simple to me, but for some reason a lot of people just can't grasp it.

author: @AminCad
processed_text: It should be noted that America became the world's super power during the late 19th century, and the greatest percentage increase in standard of living, median wages, and total production occurred during this supposedly terrible free market era. The Keynesian/interventionist post-1970s era meanwhile has seen real hourly median wages actually stagnate. The inflation has masked the stagnation in economic growth by increasing metrics that measure rate of development, so the problem is not addressed

author: @AminCad
processed_text:
John is wrong about the late 19th century. New research by George Selgin has shown that the recessions during that era were much less severe than previously believed. Economic historians had previously equated nominal decreases in GDP with a recession, but in reality, real GDP, meaning GDP adjusted for inflation (deflation), was increasing during many of these deflationary periods, due to the increasing value of dollars. 

The adjusted statistics show that recessions have worsened since 1913.

author: @friendofmalibu
processed_text: Also, we sometimes we find inspiration in other fields that help us to solve problems in computer science. For instance, epidemiology has given us insights into how malware spreads on the Internet and how we can fight back. Understanding how humans hear and see has led to insights in how to teach computers to hear and see. So by being involved in interdisciplinary work like this, we get ideas from other fields that allow us to make breakthroughs on difficult problems in the field of computing.

author: @friendofmalibu
processed_text: Also, research should try to solve big problems, and identifying the genetic causes of disease is an important problem for the world. Having computer scientists partner with medical researchers leads to new ideas, new solutions and dramatic acceleration in the scientific process.

author: @friendofmalibu
processed_text: The current generation of scientific research is being driven by the collection and analysis of enormous quantities of data. This has challenged the field of computer science to invent new technologies that can scale up to what is required and provide insights that lead to new discoveries.  By being a partner in this kind of research, we learn to create computing technologies that will better serve the scientific community today and can apply to similar “big data” applications in our products.

author: @AnzaBrush
processed_text:
The current academic consensus among linguists is that no language is more or less complex than any other language, within rough approximations. Some languages may have more complexity in one category (like number of verb tenses, genders or cases), but they are invariably simpler in another category (like perhaps syntactic structure, phonetic inventory or morphology).

So I'd be curious to know what the source for your claim that Polish speakers become fluent at 16 compared to 12 is.

author: @micbier1
processed_text:
You are wrong. It is not about language usage but language structure. The hardest language to learn is: Polish: Seven Cases, Seven Genders. Average English speaker is fluent at about the age 12; Polish not until 16. Here's one trivial example of the languages complexity number 2.
English: 1 form.
Portuguese: 2 forms depending on gender.
Croatian: 7 forms depending on gender and case.
Polish: 17 forms. Depends on gender, case for all forms. Pretty much all these forms occur in regular speech.

author: @dirkmaes3786
processed_text:
But if I type "taking the Fifth" in Google, I get the Wikipedia page "Self-Incrimination Clause" in my results.  It's not something that can't be overcome.
Modern machine translation also works more like Google, not like an automated dictionary - expert system (which is too complex to program).

If you get a program to analyse Wikipedia and other data sources like, legal text, American novels and movie scripts as reference, it is capable to come up with an accurate translation.

author: @dlmaniac
processed_text: 21 Google employees disliked it.

author: @dirkmaes3786
processed_text:
It already is a useful tool.

But for a computer to translate human languages accurately requires a much deeper understanding than just reading words and understanding grammar.
The system has to be able to unravel double meanings, figure of speech, cultural symbolism, etc...
To handle that level of complexity requires a computer that is on par with the human brain in terms of computing power; this demo only scratches the surface of what's actually needed.  I estimate 23 years from now.

author: @allanrichardson3135
processed_text: Another example would be the U.S. idiom "taking the Fifth" for refusing to answer a question.  For the benefit of non-U.S. readers, this refers to the clause against forced self-incrimination in Amendment 5 of the U.S. Constitution.  Not knowing the legal history, the translation (e.g. Spanish "obtenir al quinto") makes no sense.  Be careful not to use cultural idioms with machine translation!

processed_text: There are also cultural references even in the same language.  For example, if I said that a milestone victory in some endeavor was "Gettysburg, not Appomattox" it may not make sense to someone with little knowledge of U.S. history; for a WWII buff the same idea could be "Midway, not Tokyo Bay" or "Normandy, not Berlin", meaning a significant step toward victory with a long way to go.  China probably has similar idioms not familiar to us.

author: @brandonneo7479
processed_text: You can't compare this to the Leap. They're both fantastic developments in their own right, but the Leap is a device you set by your desk meant for interacting with your computer. Digits is something you carry around with you everywhere you go, sitting on your wrist. It's bulky here, but that's because it was built with off-the-shelf parts. What's important is that the concept is sound and further development should show a workable product for end users like us to interact with our devices.

author: @beatlesooft
processed_text:
Microsoft Digits は衝撃的なインターフェイスだ。マウスのデビューとは全く別物だ。
このデバイスは人類に貢献する可能性があると私は思う。もし、軽い刺激をあたえる人工皮膚のような手袋や指サックが開発されたら、遠隔操作や遠隔手術を含む医療などのトレーニングにも効果があるだろう。危険物処理トレーニングにも役立つだろう。
また、もし、バーチャルの操作が、実際の手を動かすという発想になれば、理学医療の分野での利用も期待出来る。
さらに、簡単なことだと思うが、倍率をコントロール出来るようにプログラムすれば、ミクロ単位の操作も可能になるだろう。
そう考えるとわくわくするデバイスだ。
勿論、MSが言うように、モバイルやタブレットの分野の応用は一番早いだろう。しかし、これは多くの未来があるデバイスだ。

author: @TheStigma
processed_text:
I agree in the sense that they are not an ideal primary interface. I don't think gestures could ever replace even a mouse and keyboard on a PC.

That said - this thing has a lot of advantages as a secondary control interface since you can seamless use it together with touch or even a keyboard on-demand. For mobile devices your hands are "always on" for if you don't have a screen interface ect. This sort of control interface has its niche to thrive in.

author: @TheStigma
processed_text:
It would work fine in the dark yes, because it uses an infrared camera. That camera will pick up the heat radiation from your body that isn't part of the visual spectrum. Your body is always "glowing" with infrared light that the camera can see - even in the dark.

All that is needed for this to become a success is to get that form-factor reduced down into an inconspicuous and comfortable wrist-bracelet or glove thingy :)

author: @alngz89
processed_text: Your mouse cursor has significantly less latency, because 1. mouse polling rates are higher (125 Hz - 1000 Hz vs. 60 Hz capacitive touchscreens) 2. typically it is hardware accelerated.  Your GPU renders the mouse cursor directly onto the screen without going through application layers and without modifying the frame buffer.  The latency is probably around 20-30 ms, because you still have display refresh latency.

author: @alngz89
processed_text: Lag is much more noticeable on a touchscreen because you can detect the lag using only one sense - your vision.  Your eyes are very sensitive, and can see the disparity between your finger and the target on the screen to millimeter accuracy.  With a mousepointer, you perceive the lag after your muscular system sends signals to your brain, which inherently has 10's to 100's of ms of lag.  Also, mouse cursor movement is not a 1:1 mapping to your mouse movement.

author: @SeverAMV
processed_text:
actually, screens with 1ms response times are already available and have been for a while.

LCD screens normally have a response time of 5ms to 16ms black to black.

but OLED and AMOLED actually have a response time of around 0.01ms and lower.

the only weakness of this is that screens on mobile devices are designed to run at 60hz, which is about 16.6ms per frame, so the fastest response/shortest delay from our touch to a visual response will be 16.6ms.

author: @chaosdoc
processed_text:
A tablet will not feature ultra-fast motion. The image is mostly static, as with a computer. I assume that's the reason all LCD monitors I've ever seen are 60Hz displays.

I agree that 240Hz TVs might have some merit to them, but only when watching 3D content shot with cameras. This will work out to 120Hz per eye and it gives us a nice multiplier of 24fps, which many movies are shot at. I suspect 480Hz is a marketing gimmick :)

Basically, tablets and TVs have different functions.

author: @MikeTrieu
processed_text: And just as a further note, AMOLED screens are capable of 0.01 ms response time, which comes out to an insane 100 KHz refresh rate, so it's definitely within reason. Whether the GPU has enough oomph to push out the pixels at full HD resolution that fast is another matter.

author: @MikeTrieu
processed_text: Overkill for what purpose, though? If you're trying to track an object @ 1 m/s over 1+ m, that doesn't sound like overkill at all. We have LCD HDTVs now that can refresh up to 480 Hz for that very reason: fast motion, mostly for sports programming. 60 Hz just doesn't cut it on larger screens. The images end up looking unnatural as the video decoder tries to interpolate the "missing" pixels between frames. If it doesn't interpolate, you end up with tearing which looks even more visually jarring.

author: @chaosdoc
processed_text:
Ghosting is a real, but different issue. There are LCD monitors today with low response times (sub 8ms) which means the pixels can change from black to white, or grey to grey in that time. That is tied to the hardware the panel uses and has nothing to do with the OS, which will treat the LCD as a 60Hz device.

The refresh rate cannot be locked to a 1000 times/sec polling rate. That is way too fast to be possible and completely overkill.

author: @MikeTrieu
processed_text: Congratulations, you win this entire comment section!

author: @MikeTrieu
processed_text: Yes they do. They're just specialized displays engineered in the lab, not mass manufactured. The future isn't widely distributed yet.

author: @MikeTrieu
processed_text: The refresh rate matters when you're dealing with large displays and rapid movement. The faster the refresh, the less "ghosting" or "tearing" the user perceives and the more fluid the experience feels. If we're trying to achieve maximum realism, the refresh rate MUST be locked to the digitizer's polling rate. You think this demo looks bad with just a tablet sized display? Just you wait until we have augmented reality eyewear and the display size is as big as your peripheral vision can handle.

author: @shockeye42
processed_text:
Well, this is a controlled test, so it's hard to say. This is a totally custom build, and software causes a lot of the latency. The latency between hardware and software may need to catch up before it's possible to get down to that benchmark in consumer devices. Anyone who has worked with live audio processing on a computer knows that 1ms is just utterly insane.

I doubt the test was done on a tablet though, The screen was probably hooked up to a purpose-built computer.

author: @shockeye42
processed_text:
Why does this kindof thing always collapse into a Windows vs. Apple fanboy circlejerk? Both sides are being ridiculous.

The Microsoft Research department are brilliant folks, and 1ms latency is truly amazing. This is a spectacular benchmark, and a job very well done. I'd love to see further testing through a full software stack, since most of the latency currently resides in software. Even 5-10ms latency would be a fantastic improvement.

Sincerely, an Apple (UNIX) geek.

author: @shockeye42
processed_text:
Well, artists already have Wacom Cintiq and the like if they are serious about it. The artists I know wouldn't want to use their fingers for a digital medium, as it just isn't very practical; and I do know artists who paint with their fingers, but that's something you can feel, so it's totally different.

The latency on Cintiq is actually fairly good, as it isn't actually a touch screen. The position and pressure information is transmitted from the pen over RF. Dead simple.

author: @shockeye42
processed_text:
Not necessarily. I am an Apple user, and I think this is BRILLIANT! A job very well done by the Microsoft Research team. Latency will definitely be the benchmark for touch hardware.

I assume it's a custom stack front-to-back, so I'm curious what the round-trip latency will be through a full OS stack. Based on my experience with live audio and MIDI hardware, I'm guessing no better than 3-10ms; which would still be totally amazing, but likely very price-prohibitive for a lot of consumers.

author: @WarrenMooreIII
processed_text: @thehyperadvisor First, the sampling rates of digitizers in today's products are not high enough. In this video, the highest sampling rate shown is roughly 1000 Hz. Current products are closer to 50-60Hz. But even if you sample that fast, you still have to draw the screen really fast to ensure smooth animation. It takes a lot of computational power to simultaneously track and draw that fast with reasonable fidelity, which is why it'll be a while before we see things like this on the market.

processed_text:
Just to settle a question in comments: Microsoft didn't invent the tablet computer.  There were touchscreen-focused computing devices before Tablet PC showed up in 2002.  And all that was, at first, was a Windows PC with pen support grafted on top.

Apple didn't 'steal' anything.  Remember the Newton? You know, from 1992?  Your iPad owes more to that -- a mobile-optimized OS, something truly portable -- than a Tablet PC. Kudos to Microsoft for its new touch research... just make something of it!

author: @WiztotheIzzard
processed_text: This is not the same as a stabilizer or image stabilization, infact, it's quite the opposite. This is moving both the point IR source and camera in the same direction and speed. This causes the light points move with it, the points the sensor sees are static in relation to the sensor itsself (at negligible reduction of resolution), while the images from all other sensors are moving in random different speeds, relative to the one  Kinect, putting them in a blur... Thus, easier to filter out.
